Hi,

The remote is wrong.

You need to have to do something similar to #6 http://bioconductor.org/developers/how-to/git/maintain-github-bioc/.

Your remote should look like this, (but instead of BiocGenerics , it should be your package name) and (instead of <developer> it should be your GitHub username).

git remote -v

origin  git at github.com<mailto:git at github.com>:<developer>/BiocGenerics.git (fetch)
origin  git at github.com<mailto:git at github.com>:<developer>/BiocGenerics.git (push)
upstream    git at git.bioconductor.org<mailto:git at git.bioconductor.org>:packages/BiocGenerics.git (fetch)
upstream    git at git.bioconductor.org<mailto:git at git.bioconductor.org>:packages/BiocGenerics.git (push)

Please also take a look at the documentation we have here http://bioconductor.org/developers/how-to/git/.

It is very helpful. Can you give me your old GitHub account and new GitHub account links?

Best,

Nitesh

